label: University of Pennsylvania LJS 295: Risālah al-sharafīyah fī al-nisab al-taʼlīfīyah
attribution: Provided by the University of Pennsylvania Libraries
description:
Summary: Treatise on the theory of music whose title translates as the Sharafian treatise on musical proportion. Written in 5 discourses with subjects including acoustics and sound, intervals, consonance and dissonance, the Arabic transcription of the 15 Greek names for notes, rhythm, and performance. The treatise is followed by an anonymous commentary (f. 41-56).
        Language: Persian
        Support: paper
        Extent: 
        Collation: Paper, 61 + ii; 1⁶ 2¹⁴ 3⁶ 4¹⁴ 5-6⁸ 7⁴(+1); [1-75], modern pagination in eastern arabic numerals in ink (f. 1v-38v), upper outer corners. Catchwords on each leaf of treatise (f. 1-37), some trimmed away, lower left verso.
        Layout: Treatise written in 15 long lines (f. 1-38) with text block framed in ink fillet borders; commentary written in 14 long lines (f. 41-56).
        Script: Written in nastaʻlīq script by 2 hands (treatise f. 1-38, commentary f. 41-56), with treatise headings in thuluth script.
        Decoration: Illuminated headpiece (f. 1v); thuluth headings in gold, diagrams and tables in red and black, and selected characters and words in red ink throughout treatise; tables in red and black and numerals and selected words in red in commentary.
        Binding: Morocco, gilt-stamped; catchwords and one leaf (f. 30) in the treatise and marginal notes in the commentary show signs of trimming.
        Origin: Written in Persia, now Iran, in A.H. 815 (1412).
        Cite as:	
        UPenn LJS 295
